Abstract Base Classes (ABC)

What ABC and @abstractmethod are and why we use them
A class with abstract methods cannot be instantiated directly
Any subclass must implement all abstract methods or it also becomes abstract

Multiple Inheritance

How Python resolves method conflicts using MRO (Method Resolution Order)
Why super().__init__() is important in multiple inheritance
How EliteCard(Card, Combatable, Magical) combines three interfaces

Design Patterns

Strategy Pattern — defines a family of algorithms (AggressiveStrategy) that can be swapped at runtime via configure_engine()
Abstract Factory Pattern — CardFactory defines the interface, FantasyCardFactory is the concrete implementation that creates themed objects
Why these patterns promote flexibility and decoupling

OOP Pillars

Polymorphism — same method name (play, attack) behaves differently per class
Encapsulation — each class manages its own state (rating, wins, losses)
Inheritance — TournamentCard inherits from Card, Combatable, Rankable

Python Specifics

__class__.__name__ to get the class name as a string
isinstance() vs __class__.__name__ checks
@abstractmethod decorator behavior
Why __init__.py makes a folder a package

Interface Design

Difference between an abstract interface and a concrete class
Why separating Combatable, Magical, Rankable into separate interfaces gives flexibility — a card can implement only what it needs


**`__init__.py`**
- Why it exists — marks a directory as a Python package
- The role of `__all__` — controls what gets exported when someone does `from ex4 import *`
- Difference between having imports in it vs leaving it empty

**Module System**
- Difference between `python3 main.py` and `python3 -m ex4.main`
- Why `-m` is needed when using relative imports across packages
- How Python resolves import paths (`ex0.Card`, `ex2.Combatable`, etc.)

**Type Hints**
- What `-> dict`, `-> list`, `-> str` mean
- `str | int | None` union types (Python 3.10+)
- Why they don't enforce anything at runtime — they're just hints

**`super()`**
- How `super().__init__()` works in a chain of inherited classes
- What happens if you don't call it

**Bubble Sort vs Built-in Sort**
- Why we replaced `sorted()` with a manual bubble sort — to avoid `lambda`
- Trade-offs: readability vs constraints

**Encapsulation of State**
- Why `TournamentPlatform` owns the `cards` dict and `matches_played` counter
- Why cards don't know about each other — the platform manages relationships

**Concrete vs Abstract**
- You should be able to clearly explain which classes are abstract and which are concrete in each exercise
- `GameStrategy`, `CardFactory`, `Combatable`, `Magical`, `Rankable` → abstract
- `AggressiveStrategy`, `FantasyCardFactory`, `EliteCard`, `TournamentCard` → concrete